There's some confusion over the terminology here, which is [explained in more detail](https://jujucharms.com/docs/stable/developer-layers#what-are-layers?) in the docs. I think the source of the confusion is that, while in a technical sense "layer" is the correct term since the charm layer is technically a type of layer, and there are even some charm layers that can themselves be used as base layers as well, if you're running `charm build` on it, it really is specifically a "charm layer" in that usage.

@hatched: The reason why it's important to use the term "layer" here is to distinguish it from from the output of the `charm build` step, which is the "built charm", or just "the charm" in the usual usage of the term (i.e., the thing that's actually deployed).  The `repo` key is specifically there to act as a pointer back to the source layer for the charm, for the `charm pull-source` command, so that the charm can be built from scratch again (or at least just so those interested in seeing the un-built source can find it).

That said, I don't think there's anything lost by being more precise in the language here by saying "charm layer" rather than just "layer" (or possibly even "charm layer source").  Do you think that would be sufficiently less confusing, @hatched?  @marcoceppi?

