I added some more debugging printouts in the library and figured out that it is unable to decode the destination-port flow component (Type 5 - the actual error message is a bit misleading) in case of an IPv6 flow. For IPv4 flows this works fine.

The flow-spec that we are sending via EXAbgp is:

      flow {
         route {
            match {
               source fd50:ff:ff::3/128/0;
               destination fd50:3:ff::ffff/128/0;
               destination-port =80; ### this is the first component that fails to get decoded by exabgp
               protocol tcp;
            }
            then {
               accept;
            }
         }
      }

This behaviour can be seen for all flow components are subclasses (flow-components) of IPv4 _and_ IPv6:

class FlowIPProtocol (IOperationByte,NumericString,IPv4): <- not for this component
class FlowNextHeader (IOperationByte,NumericString,IPv6): <- not for this component
class FlowAnyPort (IOperationByteShort,NumericString,IPv4,IPv6): <- but for this (because it is IPv4 and IPv6)
class FlowDestinationPort (IOperationByteShort,NumericString,IPv4,IPv6): <- also for this (because it is IPv4 and IPv6)
 
The array that is build from these classes in the lines following "for content in dir():" does not contain IPv6 components when they are also a subclass of IPv4 at the same time.

