> Have just written a version of spatial softmax for a fixed number of dimensions.

Just to clarify, what you've written is not what's usually referred to as a spatial softmax. Spatial softmax is usually understood to be a softmax across the channels per location, not vice versa. See #710.

> Haven't run it yet, so, may need to update...but just dropping this here in case it helps, or in case you see an obvious error??

Well, I think there's something wrong with the dot product and summation, and you will want to use an expression with `T.arange` instead of wrapping it as a shared variable (`np.linspace` won't like the symbolic `h` and `w` anyway). Similarly for the temperature if it's not learned; just directly set `self.temperature = temperature` instead of wrapping it as a shared variable. Other than that, it might work. If you're planning to train on this, it'd be more straightforward to just return `softmax_4D` and use categorical cross-entropy loss, though (also adapted to use the correct axes).

There's a softmax layer implementation at https://github.com/f0k/Lasagne/tree/spatial-softmax which is based on dimshuffle-reshape-softmax-reshape-dimshuffle. As a more direct implementation that precludes Theano's graph optimizations and thus has to be numerically stable itself, I've written the following:
```python
def spatial_logsoftmax(x, axis=1):
    x = x - T.max(x, axis, keepdims=True)
    return x - T.log(T.sum(T.exp(x), axis, keepdims=True))

def log_categorical_crossentropy(preds, truth, axis=-1):
    if truth.ndim == preds.ndim:
        return -T.sum(truth * preds, axis=axis)
    else:
        assert preds.ndim == 2
        assert truth.ndim == 1
        assert axis in (1, -1)
        return -preds[T.arange(truth.shape[0]), truth]
```
The former can be used as a nonlinearity (you'll need to use `functools.partial` if you want to change the `axis`, sorry about that, that's why it'd be a `Softmax` class in Lasagne), the latter as a cost function. That implementation of the cost function requires the targets to be one-hot-encoded.

